<TEXT>
rescuers used cherrypickers crowbars 
and their bare hands friday to burrow through tons of rubble from a 
collapsed department store pulling out six miracle survivors 
in a race with rain 90degree heat and dehydration 
the death toll in the thursday afternoon collapse of the amigo 
store rose to 15 late friday night when three more bodies were 
spotted in the debris and more were feared dead eleven bodies 
were removed 10 of those identified and four other bodies 
remained under the rubble said police sgt dean poos 
at least 47 were injured and officials feared anyone still 
buried alive would not survive 
right now hope is all that is driving the rescue effort that 
is fading as time goes by said police lt victor rodriguez 
because of the 90degree heat at this point the greatest 
danger to the people in that building is if we dont get to them 
the people if they are in a trapped area dont have any access to 
fluids said dr richard plantes 
work crews limited to 30miute shifts to prevent dehydration 
were using frontend loaders and other heavy equipment a yellow 
and white canopy shaded what once had been a threestory 
30000squarefoot store 
a new worry arose in the afternoon as clouds rolled in from the 
east threatening a repeat of torrential rains that caused the roof 
to cave in 
we dont want to go in there and find somebody drowned said 
poos 
the rescue crews also worried that the one remaining wall along 
an alley would collapse if they worked too fast 
rescuers planned to work through the night friday under portable 
lights poos said 
the crews could be heard cheering occasionally when they thought 
they heard heard noise within the debris but poos said the sounds 
did not lead to finding any more survivors 
weve had many situations when they thought they heard things 
and it turns out to be nothing he said weve got a lot of 
people out there who have been working real hard for a long time 
and the slightest thing that will give them hope can set cheers 
off 
its frustrating because you want to go in there and tear 
everything out but you need to take into consideration that if you 
tear things out you endanger the people in there said mayor 
ygnacio garza 
six survivors one a screaming toddler were freed friday 
morning from the debris where they had been buried nearly a day 
the six were two adults a boy and a girl both 8 the toddler a 
girl about 2 and a 14yearold girl 
cries from the children feedback from microphones and seismic 
tools and dogs trained to search for humans led the rescue crews 
to the survivors 
cheers and wild applause erupted from 300 onlookers as each 
survivor was lifted from the sweltering tangle of concrete 
the children had been terrified said richard schwand a red 
cross nurse from corpus christi as soon as one starts screaming 
its kind of contagious they all start going for it 
the scene grew quiet when electronic equipment was used 
authorities cleared traffic for two square blocks and asked people 
to shut down generators and engines so the microphones could pick 
up even the slightest sound 
the seismic equipment could detect a gentle tapping sound at 
1000 feet said jeff kravitz chief of mine safety operations with 
the department of labors mine safety and health administration 
survivors if any were asked to tap 10 times by searchers 
with loudspeakers speaking in english and spanish but no taps 
sounded and other noise that would be expected from alert 
survivors was absent kravitz said 
heavy equipment moved in but schwand said he feared only bodies 
would be found now its just the smell said schwand 
theres dead people under there and not just one im sure 
the victims were presumed to have been in the store when its 
roof caved in taking the walls with it after 2 inches of rain 
fell in less than 30 minutes thursday the national weather service 
said the collapse could have been caused by the weight of rain 
the 2yearold survivor appeared to have been protected by 
some other people around her who are believed dead said 
rodriguez 
the 14yearold was wedged between two concrete slabs every 
time theres movement the slabs hit her in the head said pamela 
downing of the citys public utilities board she called the girl a 
miracle child for having survived 
a brownsville maintenance worker freddie gonzalez 34 took 
advantage of his 4foot8 frame to snake his way through the heaps 
of concrete widening a path for two workers who followed 
it was a little bit hot gonzalez said the people were 
running out of oxygen that was their major complaint we ran a 
little tube through a small hole then we made a bigger hole and 
put in a bigger pipe to get air to the victims 
other rescuers dug a makeshift 17foot tunnel to reach some of 
those trapped doctors reached in to check vital signs of the 
victims said johnny economedes head of one rescue team 
among those injured slightly was store owner bernard levin 67 
who was working a cash register at the time 
it was a wellbuilt building and we still dont know what 
caused it to collapse levin said 
the 40yearold concrete structure housed the store on the first 
floor with the other two floors vacant economedes said 
</TEXT>
