the american who trained dolphins for the 
television series flipper said he is leaving for china on 
saturday to try to save endangered river dolphins from extinction 
ric obarry who has been working with dolphins for 25 years 
said only about 300 freshwater dolphins or baiji remain in 
the polluted yangtze river 
the problem is that 10 percent of the worlds population lives 
along that river he said in an interview from hong kong where 
he arrived monday from the united states 
its not a traditional pollution problem involving chemical 
waste but animal and human waste obarry said 
the chinese plan to block off a loop in the yangtze for a 
dolphin preserve but he said this might not be the solution 
because of the yangtzes pollution 
obarry would like to move the dolphins to taihu a lake near 
nanjing on the yangtze in southeastern china he believes this 
might be the only way to save them from extinction 
the survival of the river dolphins he said is not a chinese 
problem but a world problem a human problem 
obarry 48 decided to go to china after a meeting in miami 
with zhou kaiya dean of the nanjing normal university when he 
heard about the problems facing the river dolphins 
he borrowed 3000 from his 16yearold sons college fund for 
the trip but said he also is looking for corporate sponsorship for 
the project 
i dont have a lot of money but i have lots of patience 
