<TEXT>
the martyrdom of saint sebastian mixes 
dancing with the slow motion of some oriental theater and with the 
gestures martha graham uses to denote passions 
unfortunately it doesnt mix them enough before the 3 hours 
are over a viewer loses interest and becomes restless 
the slowmotion tableaux are interesting at first slowing a 
viewer into serenity the best of saint sebastian is the 
dancing but that frequently stops and with narration in french 
the story is tediously acted out martha graham has her dancers 
gesture while dancing sustaining tension 
robert wilson known for creating long operas along with modern 
composers has created a long ballet his first with japanese 
classical dancer suzushi hanayagi 
the paris opera ballet which premiered it in march is ending 
its threeweek metropolitan opera season this weekend with the 
american premiere of the work 
the martyrdom of saint sebastian is beautiful the final 
scene is paradise white grass bears and monkeys with a 
breathtaking bright white light costumes and sets are wonderful 
with large striking images like the lily which comes from above 
filling the backdrop as its petals open 
sylvie guillem was always marvelous to look at as saint 
sebastian she is lovely and has total muscle control and grace 
when she stood in front of a pillar in white sarong to be shot by 
arrows it was the pose of a 1930s hollywood star but miss guillem 
was so convincing as saint sebastian that nobody snickered 
when patrick dupond as the emperor danced he looked splendid 
michael denard was effective as a second saint sebastian 
program notes were extensive enough to make everything clear 
the text was written for a fivehour ballet in 1911 claude debussy 
composed the music 
wilson wrote a 20th century prologue directed and collaborated 
on sets and lighting 
the small amount of dancing in saint sebastian however 
reminds one of the claim made for some great voices that they would 
be fascinating reading the entire phone book its best not to put 
that to the test 
