<TEXT>
a sixday visit by soviet leader mikhail 
gorbachev beginning monday provides polish authorities a chance to 
highlight their own restructuring of politics and the economy 
party leaders say it will strengthen proreform forces in poland 
in public statements and private conversations officials have 
expressed delight that gorbachev is arriving fresh from his 
triumphs at a special party congress in moscow and they stress 
parallels between soviet perestroika and polish socialist 
renewal 
soviet perestroika helps polish renewal and vice versa 
said stefan staniszewski polands foreign affairs spokesman 
poland a sometimes unruly communist ally straddling the pathway 
between moscow and western europe is vital to the soviet union 
the trip appears designed mainly to reinforce ties between the two 
countries during an era when each is embarking on dramatic 
political changes 
gorbachev who is personally popular in poland also will be 
working to overcome a traditional antipathy among poles toward 
russians that has existed for centuries 
it is unclear however if he will defuse the single most 
painful issue between the two peoples admitting that soviet forces 
massacred 4000 polish officers in katyn forest in the ukraine in 
1940 
official polish and soviet histories have maintained the 
massacre was committed by the nazis in 1941 contrary to evidence 
in the west and the belief of most poles a polishsoviet 
historical commission charged last year with correcting blank 
spots in history has been reexamining the question amid signals 
that soviet responsibility finally would be acknowledged 
but polish officials prior to gorbachevs arrival were playing 
down the possibility of a dramatic admission by the soviet leader 
saying it is a matter of ongoing research 
gorbachev will say something about the issue generally 
because of polish feelings said one polish official who 
requested anonymity how he will say it we dont know 
since assuming leadership of the communist party of the soviet 
union in 1985 gorbachev has been to poland twice for a party 
conference and a warsaw pact meeting but polish authorities say 
this is his first fullscale ceremonial visit 
in addition to meeting polish leader gen wojciech jaruzelski 
and addressing the sejm or parliament gorbachev will travel south 
to the medieval polish capital of krakow and to the northwestern 
baltic port city of szczecin where he will address shipyard 
workers 
a side trip will take him to the tatra mountain village of 
poronin where vladimir i lenin spent two years in exile from 
czarist russia before returning to lead the bolshevik revolution of 
1917 
gorbachevs wife raisa will visit the former nazi death camp 
of auschwitzbirkenau where 4 million people were murdered before 
the camps liberation by the red army on jan 27 1945 
after the bilateral portion of the trip ends thursday 
gorbachev jaruzelski and party chiefs from the other five warsaw 
pact nations meet for two days in warsaw gorbachev returns to 
moscow on saturday 
squeezed between a recalcitrant apparatus slowing reforms and an 
active opposition movement spearheaded by the outlawed solidarity 
trade union leaders of the communist polish united workers party 
say the visit will provide them a political boost 
it is without doubt that mr gorbachevs stay in poland will 
strengthen those who are aiming at reconstruction said politburo 
member mieczyslaw rakowski at a news conference thursday 
gorbachev is expected to endorse the polish reforms 
undercutting the hardliners traditional reliance on their ties to 
moscow while emphasizing that the party should be the agent of 
change and not outside dissenters 
opposition spokesmen have said the visit will have an important 
effect in determining how far the government can go towards 
political pluralism but rakowski dismissed such expectations 
the question of the opposition is an internal one he said 
the visit will have no influence on the existing relations 
the visit comes two months after a wave of strikes that 
contained echoes of the 198081 labor upheaval in poland and 
gorbachev could use his meeting with shipyard workers in szczecin 
to address the issue of worker demands 
poland is the soviet unions largest east bloc ally putting 
szczecin on the itinerary also underlined polands security 
interest in the alliance 
the city is part of the western territories secured for poland 
from defeated germany at the end of world war ii and official 
propaganda stresses that soviet strength helps guarantee the 
existing borders 
authorities also say they expect gorbachev to speak on eastwest 
relations during the visit 
</TEXT>
