<TEXT>
the california shield law doesnt exempt 
journalists from giving eyewitness accounts when called on to 
testify an appeals court ruled 
arguments by lawyers from the los angeles times that a reporter 
and photographer were protected from disclosing unpublished 
information regarding an arrest they witnessed were unanimously 
rejected thursday by the threejustice 2nd appellate district court 
in los angeles 
reversing a superior court ruling the justices said reporters 
have the same duty as any bystander if called to testify about what 
they witnessed in public 
i think the shield law was never intended to protect news 
reporters said gerry ensley a long beach deputy city 
prosecutor it was intended to protect reporters confidential 
sources 
in cases where reporters arent protecting confidential sources 
there is no basis to differentiate the newspersons observation 
of the event from that of any other citizen said the opinion 
written by justice robert devich 
the ruling takes effect 30 days from thursday 
times general counsel william niese said a request for a state 
supreme court review was likely 
if reporters are converted into automatic witnesses the 
ability of reporters to retain their objectivity and be objective 
witnesses would be seriously undermined niese said 
the case stemmed from the prosecution of a long beach man for 
alleged possession of brass knuckles in september 1986 
sean patrick delaney 21 contended that police never asked his 
permission to search his jacket pocket where officers allegedly 
found the weapon 
reporter roxana kopetman and former photographer roberto 
santiago bertero witnessed the search and arrest but their news 
account did not mention whether officers asked such permission 
called to testify in municipal court ms kopetman and bertero 
declined to answer questions about whether permission was requested 
they contended that since the information wasnt included in the 
story the shield law protected them from having to answer both 
were found in contempt of court 
</TEXT>
