<TEXT>
the explosion and fire that destroyed the piper 
alpha oil rig wednesday night was the worlds worst oilfield 
disaster claiming 166 lives this is a reconstruction compiled 
from official logs and interviews with survivors 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the men from the 12hour day shift 
were going to bed on the piper alpha oil platform and derek 
ellington was in the control room he heard a gas leak screaming 
like a banshee 
it was 931 pm wednesday in the north sea 120 miles from 
scotland thirty seconds later an explosion and fire began 
devouring the platform which had 230 men aboard 
not until 27 minutes after the initial explosion did word reach 
the mainland the aberdeen coast guard picked up a distress signal 
from the supply vessel lowland cavalier near the manmade island 
which was 649 feet tall twothirds submerged and supported by 
steel stilts planted in the seabed 
four minutes later at 1002 eoin kerr a telecommunications 
officer in scotland heard a man say from the piper alpha the 
radio rooms on fire were abandoning the rig 
kerr heard nothing more 
within one minute of the first distress call royal air force 
rescue helicopters scrambled and a nimrod reconnaissance aircraft 
headed to the scene 
there was a big bang and i knew there had been an explosion 
said james mcdonald 50 who managed to get off the piper alpha 
the rig was plunged into darkness 
he and some others tried to leave the crews quarters but the 
flames were shooting into the doors for about threequarters 
of an hour we were sitting inside nobody seemed to know what to 
do 
the nimrod pilot garfield porter could see the horizon stained 
orange with fire from 80 miles away approaching at 15000 feet 
the whole area was lit up and the flames were very high into the 
sky he said 
helicopter pilots said they felt the heat from more than a mile 
away choppers swept in low and dropped ropes to survivors in the 
water 
a converted trawler on standby duty lowered lifeboats that 
collected 37 survivors a lifeboat from the support ship sandhaven 
vanished into the flames 
fire spread rapidly turning metal girders redhot and bringing 
decks crashing down in halfmolten heaps 
the men faced a hard choice stay aboard and hope aid got to 
them before the flames or jump into a sea that was cold enough 
below the burning oil to kill them even on a clear summer night 
the water temperature was 57 degrees 
burning oil was spreading across the few bare patches of water 
remaining and the decision had to be made quickly 
i decided to get myself out mcdonald said i wasnt going 
to sit down and get burned to death you either stayed where 
you were and burned to death or you tried to get out 
roy carey an instrument technician said it was a case of 
fry and die or jump and try 
mcdonald said he had to push past other men clogging the 
stairways then through the flames onto the drill deck which was 
not yet burning he slithered down a pipe and dropped the last few 
feet into the water 
when he looked up the only thing standing was the drill 
derrick there was no accommodation living deck no rig no 
helideck just flames coming shooting out of the sea 
carey dived 50 feet into the water debris showered down and 
bodies floated past him i found my head was being cooked he 
said i had to keep ducking down to get it cool 
the coast guard appealed for ships to help the 15 helicopters 
and 30 responded including a sixship nato task force that radioed 
at 1036 it was breaking off maneuvers to join the search 
a supply and support vessel the tharos sprayed the fire with 
seawater but the only result was clouds of steam 
there was nothing anybody could do said tony sinnett who 
watched from the tharos it was like the platform had been hit by 
an atomic bomb 
porter the reconnaissance pilot said the flames shot hundreds 
of feet into the sky 
at 1130 pm lifeboats had picked up 25 survivors the crews 
quarters were an inferno 
windows and the emergency door were cracking under the intense 
heat there must have been at least 100 men in there said harry 
calder 35 
it was sheer panic a lot of guys were lying on the floor 
just trying to breathe we had towels and we were just dipping them 
in anything to help us breathe 
he managed to get out but believes all the others died 
at 1124 the tharos radioed that underwater explosions of 
escaping gas were forcing it to retreat at three minutes after 
midnight it said everyone likely to have survived had been picked 
up 
the search continued occidental petroleum which owns the 
platform said the last of 64 survivors was rescued at 305 am 
at 1246 am the living quarters sank beneath the sea when the 
nato ships arrived next morning there was nothing left to do but 
search for bodies 
seventeen had been found by friday night 
only about onequarter of the rig remained standing thick 
support girders were bent double and flames still flickered on the 
wreck 
in aberdeen kay harney watched the scenes on television and 
remembered the telephone call wednesday night from her boyfriend 
eddie crowden 
he said he was bored with his job of checking lifeboats and 
safety equipment on the piper alpha 
that was at 925 pm 
eddie crowdens name was not on the list of survivors 
</TEXT>
