<TEXT>
irans small fleet of f14 fighters has 
become one focus of attention in the investigation of why the us 
missile cruiser vincennes shot down an iranian airliner with 290 
people aboard 
the pentagon has said transponder signals from the iran air 
airbus a300 civilian aircraft caused the warship to mistake it for 
an iranian f14 
the americanbuilt fighters called the tomcat are part of a 
depleted inventory of combatready warplanes that iran has used 
sparingly in its war with iraq 
the swingwing interceptors were one of the most advanced 
aircraft in the world when about 80 of them were sold to shah 
mohammed reza pahlavis air force in the mid1970s 
after nearly eight years of warfare tehrans f14 force was 
believed to have dwindled to fewer than 10 operational aircraft 
according to some military analysts 
us officials put their numbers somewhat higher in the 
teens and have said in recent days that the force may have been 
increased by irans success in acquiring badly needed spare parts 
the grumman aircraft saw combat action in 1985 since then it 
has been used primarily for its powerful radar systems that can 
alert other iranian fighters to the approach of iraqi warplanes 
the operational area of the f14s was around irans kharg island 
oil terminal in the northern persian gulf and over the coastal 
sealanes used by tehrans oil shuttle tankers carrying oil from 
kharg to the larak island terminal in the strait of hormuz 
on feb 9 iran claimed it shot down three iraqi jets during a 
raid on kharg 
days later us assistant defense secretary richard armitage 
disclosed in a pentagon briefing that one iraqi aircraft was shot 
down by an f14 using a usmade sidewinder airtoair missile 
he said it was the f14s first effective use in combat that 
weve seen in several months 
us officials said recently that some of the f14s had been 
shifted from the northern gulf to the big military base at bandar 
abbas on the strait of hormuz 
it was from bandar abbas that the iran air airbus took off last 
sunday 
us sources who spoke on condition they not to be named said 
friday that the transfer of f14s from bushehr to bandar abbas may 
have been motivated by iraqs devastating longrange air strike on 
may 14 on the larak island terminal in the strait where 
international tankers pick up the oil brought south from kharg 
in that raid the worlds biggest ship the seawise giant which 
iran uses as a storage and transfer tanker and four others were 
damaged 
the f14s were airborne in the skies around the strait in the 
days prior to the iran air incident but had not taken part in any 
combat action as interceptors equipped with airtoair missiles 
they are not designed for ttacks on ships 
in addition to the f14s iran has some aging f4 phantoms and 
some f5s acquired from the united states during the shahs regime 
although they watch the aircraft carefully us warships in the 
gulf have not faced many serious threats from irans warplanes the 
iranian fighters generally give the americans a wide berth and 
observe good radio protocol when challenged us officers say 
us commanders have worried most about iraqi pilots 
particularly in view of the may 17 1987 attack on the missile 
frigate stark by an iraqi mirage in which 37 american crewmen 
died washington officially accepted iraqs explanation that the 
attack was a mistake 
several subsequent incidents including one in which a us 
missile cruiser richmond k turner came within a second of shooting 
down three iraqi warplanes led the two governments to work out 
procedures to protect us warships from another iraqi attack in 
the northern gulf 
us officials said they had no information to support a 
published report that another us missile cruiser the halsey had 
fired a flare in a brush with two iranian f14s on july 2 the day 
before the airbus disaster 
this is the first weve heard of the halsey firing a flare or 
any of those other details said one source who has access to 
operational reports and spoke on condition he not be named 
the pentagon on thursday released the transcript of a radio 
exchange between the halsey on station in the northern gulf and 
an iranian f14 on that same day 
the brief exchange was presented by the us officials to show 
that the iranians routinely respond to such queries from the us 
navy ships in the gulf 
the pentagon says the vincennes and another us ship issued 12 
warnings to the iran air jetliner before it was shot down 
there have been some reports in the aftermath of the tragedy 
that the two sides do not routinely communicate by radio 
the idea that the iranians dont answer our queries is 
baloney said one american source added another to say that 
there are routine exchanges between us ships and iranian military 
aircraft is an accurate statement 
