a judge has forbidden the city to hire 
firefighters while the state investigates complaints that physical 
tests for the job discriminate against women 
ramsey county judge joanne smith issued a temporary injunction 
thursday at the request of state human rights commissioner steve 
cooper who said the investigation will take about 45 days smith 
set a hearing on continuation of the injunction for july 14 
the complaints were lodged after none of 17 women who recently 
took the firefighter test passed 
the city already has sent offers of employment to 25 men who 
passed the test before being hired the men must pass medical 
exams and background checks but smith specifically prohibited the 
fire department from following through on the job offers until the 
ban is lifted 
she included six minority men in the ban despite a request by 
the southern minnesota regional legal services that they be allowed 
to take offered jobs 
attorney bruce beneke argued that the minorities should be 
exempt from the injunction because all but one of them were chosen 
under affirmative action hiring rules to reverse racial 
discrimination 
ten women who failed the test filed a discrimination suit 
claiming the test was rigged to favor physical attributes more 
common to men and that the cutoff score was set artificially high 
the cutoff was determined by 45 volunteers now working as 
firefighters who have good excellent or superior physical ratings 
firefighters in poorer condition and men in higher ranks were not 
allowed to participate in the socalled norming test 
women who work as firefighters in nearby minneapolis also were 
not allowed to volunteer 
