<TEXT>
recent advances made by the soviet union in 
the production of livestock products should continue well into the 
1990s if some technical and policy problems can be smoothed out an 
agriculture department analyst said friday 
a drive to increase meat and dairy production to upgrade soviet 
diets has been an important factor in moscows decisions to import 
large quantities of us grains when domestic harvests have been 
short 
the policies now in place or in the process of implementation 
portend improved performance compared with the late 1970s and early 
1980s but they will leave substantial productivity potential 
unrealized said edward c cook of the departments economic 
research service 
between 1982 and 1987 increases in soviet output of meat and 
milk marked a notably reversal of the downtrends between 1977 
and 1982 cook wrote in a new report about the soviet unions 
livestock sector 
milk yields increased per cent a year after 1982 and the 
perhead productivity of hogs and cattle increased 2 percent and 
34 percent a year respectively 
prospects for soviet livestock production hinge on how much 
the technical approaches particularly improvements in feed 
supplies will be pushed in coming years cook said a lack of 
coherence has continued to hinder the broad policies addressing 
pricing farm finances and agroindustrial integration 
cook said that without smoothing out these problems moscows 
policies can accomplish little more than modest improvement in 
the livestock sector 
