<TEXT>
military commanders must tell soldiers and 
airmen testing positive for the aids virus that they face discharge 
or prosecution if they dont tell sex partners of their condition 
and use condoms under new army and air force regulations 
defense lawyers in an aidsrelated courtmartial scheduled to 
start the week of july 25 at fort huachuca in southeastern arizona 
have argued that the defendant had not been ordered either to use 
condoms or to inform partners 
spelled out under the regulations and a similar navy policy 
are rules of behavior at issue in a number of cases in which 
military personnel who have tested positive for the aids virus have 
been charged with criminal offenses from aggravated assault to 
having unsafe sex without warning partners of the test results 
the military services require all personnel to submit to aids 
blood screening tests which detect the presence of antibodies and 
indicate whether a person has been exposed to the virus 
lt col greg rixon an army spokesman at the pentagon said 
recently the army regulation which became effective april 1 
requires a commander to discuss a written counseling statement with 
any soldier who has tested positive and has received medical 
counseling 
it says the commander is imposing the following restrictions 
you will verbally advise all prospective sexual partners of your 
diagnosed condition prior to engaging in any sexual intercourse 
you are also ordered to use condoms should you engage in sexual 
intercourse with a partner 
the form also states that failure to adhere to your previous 
medical counseling or the counseling i have just given you will 
subject you to administrative separation andor punishment under 
the uniform code of military justice as i see fit 
this is serious business rixon said those words take the 
form of a direct order 
we dont order them to refrain from sex i dont think we 
could do that said col harry beans staff judge advocate at 
fort huachuca 75 miles southeast of tucson but partners must be 
informed so that he or she can make an informed decision 
the upcoming courtmartial of pvt adrian g morris jr 
initiated by the army in 1987 was the militarys first 
aidsrelated prosecution morris then a private first class is 
accused of failing to warn three soldiers with whom he had sex 
including one man that he had tested positive for the virus and 
to use condoms 
his lawyers have argued that there was no order for morris to do 
either in july 1986 when he was informed of the virus potential 
danger and counseled that he should inform partners and use a 
condom 
morris courtmartial was delayed pending appeal of a blood test 
admissibility ruling 
last december a soldier at fort hood texas pleaded guilty to 
aidsrelated charges including disobeying an officers order 
virtually identical to the new regulation 
in addition several other military aidsrelated cases have been 
tried including that of a fort sill okla soldier who pleaded 
guilty to aggravated assault and of an airman at wrightpatterson 
air force base ohio who was convicted on such a charge 
recurrence of the element of assault in the cases made clear 
that we needed a very definitive guideline to assure there is a 
standardization of orders rixon said 
the air force regulation like the armys provides a form both 
the affected airman and his or her commander must sign 
acknowledging that the person has been given the directive and 
understands it 
the air force order also requires people carrying the aids virus 
to inform medical personnel treating them 
navy spokesman lt kenneth ross in washington said a navy policy 
took effect in january telling affected sailors that if they do 
not tell their sex partners of their test status they face 
administrative or disciplinary measures ross said he knew of no 
requirement that a commander issue a direct order to affected 
individuals 
</TEXT>
