<TEXT>
six cars of a packed express passenger 
train derailed and plunged into a rainswollen lake in southern 
kerala state friday killing 85 people and injuring 500 others 
authorities said 
the death toll was expected to rise because up to 200 people 
were missing 
the united news of india news agency said as many as 250 people 
were feared dead the figure could not be independently confirmed 
six brickred passenger cars tumbled into the 20 to 
30footdeep lake asthamudi and were submerged while three others 
dangled from the bridge said ik chari a spokesman for the 
indian railways ministry 
rescuers worked under flood lights as navy divers searched 
submerged cars for survivors and bodies an official at the 
accident site told the associated press by telephone 
kerala railways minister a neelalohitadasan nadar said he 
suspected poor maintenance of tracks was the cause of the accident 
it is monsoon season in coastal kerala a state known for its 
palmfringed backwaters it had rained heavily earlier friday and 
was drizzling when the cars derailed near quilon about 30 miles 
north of the state capital of trivandrum 
the engine and one coach of the 14car island express crossed a 
bridge over the lake before the passenger cars derailed about 115 
pm chari said four of the last cars remained on the track 
dozens of fishermen in long narrow boats joined in rescue 
operations below the bridge which is about 15 feet above the water 
dr fritz mario saldana a dentist told the news agency that he 
saved himself inside a submerged car by clinging to a ceiling fan 
and keeping his head above the rising water he praised fishermen 
who were at the site within minutes to save trapped passengers 
among those killed were 60 men 20 women and five children 
according to vellu kutty head constable in quilon 
at least 192 people were hospitalized in quilon and trivandrum 
after the accident including 23 who were critically injured said 
matthew john a safety official for the indian railways ministry 
others were released after treatment 
most of the passengers on the train which was heading from 
bangalore to trivandrum were military personnel and government 
officials heading home for the weekend railway officials said 
john said the train can carry up to 1700 passengers and usually 
is crowded on fridays 
television and indian news agency reports said the cars plunged 
into the water after part of the 540foot bridge caved in but 
railway officials said the cause was not yet known 
it will take a lot of investigation to determine whether it 
was sabotage or something wrong with the tracks said sp 
sharma director of the safety division of the railways ministry 
john said two spans of the bridge were damaged by the accident 
nadar told the united news of india that he discussed bad 
maintenance with railway officials recently but the officials did 
not pay much attention 
dr thomas verghese deputy director of the quilon district 
hospital told the associated press by telephone that the death 
toll was expected to rise because three cars still were under water 
we have been very busy with the tragedy we are well equipped 
to handle the tragedy he said 
trains are the major form of transport in india carrying about 
9 million people daily the vast network of the railways stretches 
over 38347 miles of rail lines 
train accidents in india are common often taking dozens of 
lives the railway ministry announced in parliament in february 
that 227 people were killed in 613 train accidents during 1987 
the worst train accident in india is listed in the guiness book 
of records as the worlds worst claiming more than 800 lives when 
a train plunged into a river in the eastern state of bihar in june 
1981 
