<TEXT>
health officials opened thousands of acres of 
oyster beds that were closed for 20 years because the 
droughtslowed mississippi river is carrying less sewage and 
industrial waste into the gulf of mexico 
the lack of moisture over the midwest and plains has left the 
mississippi flowing past new orleans at about 114000 cubic feet 
per second about a fourth of its normal flow upriver barges run 
aground on newly bared sandbars downriver a wedge of saltwater is 
edging upstream from the gulf toward drinking water intakes at new 
orleans and neighboring communities 
the river is very polluted when its flowing normally said 
jim cosgrove of the state department of health with the river flow 
dropping its spewing less pollution into coastal areas where 
oysters grow 
plaquemines parish officials estimate that about 4 million 
worth of prime oysters soon will be heading to the market from the 
areas opened thursday 
theres always perhaps a silver lining to the big clouds 
said ron dugas of the state department of state wildlife amp 
fisheries 
it looks real good said oysterman kenny fox of pointe a la 
hache these are quality oysters salty and fat and very 
productive 
fox has had leases in cox bay for 20 years but pollution had 
kept him from harvesting a single oyster 
plaquemines parish officials had been monitoring the areas daily 
for about three weeks recent samples showed that the counts of 
fecal coliform bacteria had dropped from double digit numbers to 
almost nothing 
in another indicator of the rivers weakness biologists from 
louisiana state university say saltwater fish are making their way 
up the mississippi ahead of the leading edge of salty seawater 
flowing upstream beneath the lighter river water 
without the rivers normal flow pushing the saltwater back to 
the gulf the tip of the wedge of saltwater was at new orleans 
about 100 miles from the mouth of the river and saltwater fish 
were netted about 35 miles farther upstream 
sheepshead and saltwater catfish are among the species reported 
caught by fishermen and lsu researchers say they have caught 
menhaden flounder and atlantic rays 130 miles from the mouth of 
the river 
catching saltwater fish in the area of laplace is unusual said 
allen rutherford of the lsu school of forestry wildlife and 
fisheries 
