<TEXT>
astronaut charles bolden twice rode 
a safety basket at 50 mph down a 1200foot slide for life wire 
friday to practice an emergency launch pad escape from the space 
shuttle discovery 
two safety workers rode with him on the second trip 
it was the first time humans had ridden the basket escape system 
since it was installed several years ago for the shuttle program 
astronauts and pad personnel would use the system in case of a 
fire fuel or gas leak or other emergency on the pad that gave them 
time to reach the baskets 
after a simulated emergency was declared bolden a veteran of 
one shuttle mission made his way from the cabin level of discovery 
195 feet up launch pad 39b and climbed into the basket for the 
dizzying descent 
the baskets fast fall was arrested abruptly at the bottom by a 
braking system made up of a series of increasingdensity steel 
chains that dragged through the sand in the landing zone 
had the brakes failed the basket would have been jolted to a 
stop by a net stretched across the baskets path 
once at the bottom bolden leaped from the basket and ran to the 
safety of a nearby concretelined underground bunker 
he reported the ride was smooth and then returned to the 
spacecraft cabin level and repeated the ride with two pad safety 
personnel george hoggard and albert bumgardner each of the seven 
baskets is rated to hold three people 
nasa reported both tests were completed successfully 
previous basket tests were run with sandbags and dummies for 
ballast and two sandbag tests preceded boldens first run friday 
until recently some nasa officials felt the swift ride would be 
risky and should be tried only in an actual emergency 
but with the added emphasis on safety following the loss of 
shuttle challenger and its seven crew members the space agency 
decided recently to manrate the basket system after making several 
improvements 
bolden hoggard and bumgardner volunteered for the job 
among the improvements were the addition of two baskets 
increasing the number to seven the cutting of a side exit in each 
basket to ease entry and exit adding a flame protective covering 
over the existing webbed material and the installation of an 
antirollback brake to ensure the basket stopped as quickly as 
possible 
discovery was moved to the launch pad monday to be prepared for 
the first shuttle launching since challenger exploded on jan 28 
1986 the launch is scheduled in early september 
bolden flew as pilot on the shuttle mission before the 
challenger accident he has been named to pilot another flight next 
year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

