independent counsel james mckay said friday 
the court order prohibiting any leak of his report on attorney 
general edwin meese iii has been violated and that he would 
investigate and seek sanctions against those responsible 
the new york times reported in saturdays editions that it had 
obtained portions of the report and revealed details from the 
830page document but did not identify its source 
executives of the times in new york and washington declined 
immediate comment 
one source said the times had acquired those portions of the 
report which were made available to meeses former lawyer and 
confidant e robert wallach 
both wallach and his attorney did not immediately return 
telephone calls 
mckay who did not identify the source of the leak said he 
regards this as an extremely serious development and intends to 
investigate this matter and seek sanctions against the person or 
persons responsible for this violation 
sources said mckay decided against seeking any criminal 
indictment of meese although matters discussed in the report might 
be reviewed by justice department ethics officers to see if 
administrative discipline is warranted 
the special threejudge court which appointed mckay authorized 
him to give out portions of his report to individuals who were 
mentioned in it so they could have an opportunity to submit 
rebuttal comments before the report is released publicly by the 
court they were given until july 14 to submit such comments 
mckays office said those portions were released under an order 
from the court requiring that the portions be kept confidential 
any violation of such an order would subject the violator to 
potential contempt of court penalties to be determined by the 
threejudge court mckays office said 
asked about the possibility of contemptofcourt proceedings 
appeals court judge george mackinnon head of the panel that 
appointed mckay said wed have to evaluate it when the 
situation developed obviously with the great number of people 
that are named in the report its not a great discovery to find 
that something might have leaked if the judges decided to 
proceed they would have to apply to a us attorneys office to 
make a determination on whether a contemptofcourt case would be 
pressed the judge said 
mackinnon said that the panel will proceed with its schedule 
which calls for comments to be submitted by people corporations or 
foundations named in the report by next thursday until at least 
that time the panel will not release the report publicly 
mackinnon said 
mckay also provided full copies to meeses attorneys and to 
solicitor general charles fried who for the purposes of this 
matter is acting attorney general 
james rocap one of meeses attorneys would not comment on 
mckays report despite the report that a portion of it has been 
leaked 
we agree with the independent counsel that it is reprehensible 
for anyone to violate the court order if in fact that has 
happened rocap said we intend to comply with the court order 
fully and to prepare our response on a timely basis 
mckay submitted his report to the court tuesday at the 
conclusion of a criminal investigation begun on may 11 1987 
mckay examined the involvement of meese at the request of 
wallach with scandalplagued wedtech corp in 1981 and 1982 when 
meese was white house counselor mckay also looked into meeses 
involvement again at wallachs initiative on behalf of a 1 
billion proposed iraqi oil pipeline project in 1985 
the independent counsel reviewed the attorney generals meetings 
with and decision on behalf of executives of the regional bell 
telephone companies at a time when he held 14000 in telephone 
stock 
mckay also looked into the fact that members of a washington 
real estate family through a foundation arranged to pay a 
40000ayear salary for meeses wife while leasing office space 
to the justice department 
wallach was involved with meese in both the phone stock and mrs 
meeses job 
