<TEXT>
the sharp drop in official jobless figures 
inevitably will ignite a new flareup of inflation fears since 
inflation seems to be on everyones mind 
talk to car dealers and they say folks are buying because they 
feel prices are bargains relative to what they could be tomorrow 
ask real estate people and they say couples are buying to avoid 
higher interest rates later 
brokers give similar reasons for misgivings about the future of 
stock and bond markets economists cite inflation prospects as a 
reason for forecasting an end to expansion workers use it to win 
wage increases 
inflation is the allpurpose allamerican fear resurrected 
every time a new figure comes out of the washington numbers 
factories or oil prices rise or drought spreads through farmlands 
or consumer spending rises 
in part it is a legacy of the 1970s a time when inflation 
turned the ordinary persons economic world inside out and upside 
down making fortunes for borrowers while destroying savings 
accounts that had taken years to build 
but in spite of the fears devil inflation has not arisen from 
his den he has resisted the popular view time after time and 
there is a good chance he will continue to do so after examining 
the latest employment report 
when unemployment falls to what is thought of as the full 
employment level which is now estimated to be somewhere around 5 
percent pressure is expected on wage rates and rising wages are 
an indicator of inflation 
the latest report shows that civilian unemployment fell to 53 
percent in june from 56 percent in may a consequence mainly of a 
jump of 823000 in civilian employment an extreme and unexpected 
figure 
almost nobody foresaw anything of the sort especially since the 
jobless rate had risen in may by twotenths of a percentage point 
for it to fall one month later to the lowest figure in 14 years 
just didnt fit the pattern 
however a strong possibility exists that the pattern hasnt 
changed much if at all employment and jobless figures are subject 
to adjustments and these latest figures conceivably could be 
adjusted out of existence 
the big question mark concerns the methodology specifically the 
fact that the survey week occurred late in june when students high 
school and college graduates and seasonal workers were entering the 
labor market 
in some years this sort of influx could raise the jobless rates 
sharply for this reason if a person isnt actively seeking work 
he or she is not a member of the labor force they become members 
by actively looking for work 
in years of depressed economic activity therefore an influx of 
job seekers can raise the jobless rate but not this year sluggish 
as the economy is said to be business continues to expand create 
job openings and hire 
but of perhaps more importance is that opportunities abound 
these days for youngsters even those totally unskilled at retail 
