<TEXT>
controversy over the safety of the suzuki 
samurai has accentuated a deep rift among american opinion leaders 
and the general public over a basic question what is safe 
consumer reports says the jeeplike samurai is too tall narrow 
light and short and thus tips over too easily when the driver 
swerves back and forth at high speed 
supporters say that although the samurais high center of 
gravity makes it tippier than some other vehicles it is safe in 
the hands of a competent driver 
theres no easy definition of what safe or unsafe is its 
really a continuum jeffrey miller deputy administrator of the 
national highway traffic safety administration said in a recent 
interview 
the conflict between consumerists and auto enthusiasts runs 
through the public at large said john staudenmaier a professor of 
history and technology at the university of detroit 
one approach says the design ought to make it nearly 
impossible to have an accident staudenmaier said but auto 
buffs would tend to say were not idiots 
americans make decisions about safety every time they choose 
between a car and a motorcycle or between a big heavy car and a 
small light one 
unfortunately for suzuki consumers judgments about the samurai 
have been powerfully influenced by television news clips supplied 
by consumers union that show the samurai tipping over onto its 
outriggers 
for some people the visual impact tends to overwhelm american 
suzuki motor corps recitation of favorable accident statistics 
and its counterargument that nearly any vehicle can be made to tip 
over by extreme driving maneuvers 
the fourwheeldrive samurai became one of the hottest imports 
in 1986 and 1987 because of its emotional appeal as a fun jazzy 
and liberated little box on wheels 
the charm faded in june as sales of the samurai plunged 706 
percent from their levels of a year earlier it was mainly a 
reaction to the june 2 report by consumers union the mount vernon 
nybased publisher of consumer reports 
suzuki dealers are hoping sales will recover gradually in coming 
months but that will depend partly on how often the infamous 
videotape reappears on the evening news 
editors of auto magazines tend to say that the primary 
responsibility for car safety should fall on the driver rather than 
the automaker 
any car has design intent if the design intent is exceeded 
the car is going to do something weird and spooky said dennis 
simanaitis executive editor of road amp track 
the samurai had to be built high off the ground because it is 
used offroad simanaitis said a vehicle that can drive over 
boulders and logs is by nature tippier than a lowslung sports car 
if suzuki gave no warnings it would be different but they 
have disclaimers galore simanaitis said 
suzukis television ads quote a 1986 article by car and driver 
that said if you want a rugged fourwheeldrive for the minimum 
amount of money the samurai is the only game in town 
william jeanes the magazines editor said he stands behind 
that statement 
i think every car taken to extremes can do something 
dangerous jeanes said how high is too high for a center of 
gravity i dont know the answer to that 
road amp tracks own road test did not include the swerving 
maneuver in which consumers union got the samurai to tip over 
simanaitis said he found no fault with the consumers union test but 
added if i look around hard enough i can find a test that will 
embarrass almost any vehicle except an outandout race car 
consumers union is calling on the government to develop 
industrywide standards for for a national standard on resistance to 
rollovers but the national highway traffic safety administration 
has resisted that approach in the past 
a strict formula for height weight and other characteristics 
could have the effect of banning certain classes of vehicles and 
courts have ruled that the federal agency should go to great 
lengths to avoid that miller said 
miller said the national highway traffic safety administration 
is seeking ways aside from design rules that would lessen rollover 
problems such as improving brakes 
we recognize that there are a wide variety of vehicles and 
you dont want to deprive people of vehicles that they need or want 
to use whether its for work or for pleasure he said 
