<DOCNO> AP880708-0262 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after months of delay and makeshift changes 
aimed at preventing another stock crash the two leading us 
financial markets have devised a joint plan of reforms they hope 
will lure back frightened investors 
the proposal announced thursday by the new york stock exchange 
and chicago mercantile exchange included priority treatment for 
individuals in the marketplace and an experimental system of 
coordinated trading halts triggered by a 250point drop in the dow 
jones industrial average 
the boards of both exchanges also said they would develop a 
joint policy regarding frontrunning a controversial practice 
in which traders execute an order in one market based on prior 
knowledge of an order in another market 
frontrunning has been blamed for aggravating volatility in the 
stock market and has been criticized by many investors and some 
lawmakers as a form of insider trading because it is based on 
knowledge not available to all 
the joint announcement by the new york and chicago exchanges 
addressed many key issues raised by government studies on the 
causes of the october crash such as the brady commission appointed 
by president reagan particularly the need for intermarket 
cooperation 
previously the exchanges had undertaken limited steps largely 
on their own or argued that additional regulations would hamper 
their postcrash recovery 
the announcement also reflected a growing concern in the 
securities industry about the prolonged absence of individual 
investors who have remained reluctant to participate in markets 
since the record 508point plunge in the dow average on black 
monday oct 19 for fear they are unsafe and unfair 
markets have returned to more normal patterns but there is 
still a perception that individuals are at a disadvantage in 
todays highspeed markets nyse chairman john phelan said in a 
joint statement with cme chairman leo melamed the initiatives 
approved by the boards should overcome that concern 
we have developed a program of coordinated procedures which 
serve the current needs of financial markets melamed said 
these combined initiatives demonstrate our commitment to serving 
the needs of all investors and ensuring a level playing field for 
all market participants 
all the initiatives must be approved by the securities and 
exchange commission which oversees the nations stock markets and 
the commodities futures trading commission which regulates the 
futures markets 
the steps include a new express lane system for expediting 
orders of individual investors to the nyse floor on heavy trading 
days during the crash many individuals were unable to sell their 
stock quickly because the markets system was clogged with sell 
orders from large institutional investors 
both exchanges also proposed a oneyear experimental system of 
coordinated circuit breaker mechanisms to forestall panicky 
selling when the dow average is falling rapidly 
under this system which must be approved by other exchanges in 
addition to the federal regulators all trading on the nyse would 
be halted for an hour if the dow average falls 250 points and for 
an additional two hours if the average falls an additional 150 
points the same day 
at the cme the key standard amp poors 500 stockindex future 
could fall a maximum 30 points before trading was halted in that 
market a further twohour halt would be called if the sampp index 
future fell another 20 points the same day 
because a onepoint drop in the sampp index equals approximately 
an eightpoint fall in the dow average the practical effect will 
be coordinated halts in both exchanges market officials familiar 
with the proposal said the two exchanges jointly would manage the 
exact timing of such halts 
the experimental reforms are aimed at taming the wild price 
swings that some crash studies have attributed to a trading method 
called index arbitrage in which brokerages use computers to sell 
huge blocks of stocks and buy stockindex futures or vice versa 
to profit from momentary price discrepancies 
the reforms would supercede a temporary nyse measure implemented 
in february called the collar which banned use of the nyses 
computer system for index arbitrage when the dow average rose or 
fell 50 points from the previous close some critics said the 
collar actually worsened volatility by severing an important link 
between the new york and chicago markets 
wall street firms reacted favorably to the joint announcement 
with many welcoming any step aimed at improving investor confidence 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
