<TEXT>
the freespending yuppies of today have been 
blamed for a number of lifes little economic inconveniences like 
driving up the prices of vacation homes or sportscars even 
hoarding imported pesto sauce and brie 
in the next five years they also may be partly responsible for 
a shortage of bonds that at least one noted economist is 
forecasting 
edward yardeni chief economist for prudentialbache securities 
inc in new york predicts that new demographic trends in this 
country will dampen the growth of credit demands and 
consequently the supply of bonds and notes 
todays yuppies he says are likely to become tomorrows 
couchpotato savers with a penchant for stashing away their 
cash possibly in fixedincome investments instead of borrowing to 
finance new homes expensive bmws and such 
what is transforming yuppie borrowers into couchpotato 
savers babies yardeni says in a recent report baby boomers 
who are expecting either their first or second baby tend to borrow 
a great deal of money to buy a house but once they settle down 
odds are theyll borrow less and save more 
yardeni predicts that those who do borrow either may be 
renovating an existing home or seeking a larger tradeup both of 
which probably would require less mortgage credit than a firsttime 
buyer 
he says that as a result popular mortgagebacked securities 
such as ginnie maes might shrink in supply and yields on such 
longterm bonds now in the 10percent range could fall to 6 
percent in about five years as demand outpaces supply a drop in 
yields will push up the price of existing bonds that carry higher 
rates 
but thats only part of yardenis theory he paints an equally 
rosy picture for the rest of the credit markets particularly 
treasury securities 
for one thing he says chances are the federal budget deficit 
will be declining lessening the supply of bonds 
also savings institutions are likely to increase their 
purchases of fixedincome instruments as a result of an anticipated 
greater deposit flow from these couchpotato savers yardeni 
says and government trust funds such as social security are 
expected to run a big surplus in the next few years which could 
swallow up the entire national debt by the year 2030 he says 
yardeni says the yield on the governments bellwether 30year 
bond could fall to 5 percent in five years 
we wouldnt be surprised if by the end of the decade 
investors complain about a shortage of bonds and nostagically 
recall the days when yields were above 9 percent he says 
but yardeni warns this is just one component of an overall 
view of the economy 
clearly the fatal blow to my theory would be a severe 
recession it would balloon the federal deficit and cause problems 
in the credit markets interest rates would fall but for the 
wrong reasons 
