<DOCNO> AP880708-0290 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a security and exchange commission ruling that 
prevents the issuing of separate and more powerful classes of stock 
does not seriously deplete corporate americas defensive armory 
poison pills remain the no 1 repellant of hostile bidders 
far surpassing supervoting stock which carries greater weight 
than the average common share 
indeed only 359 public companies have unequal voting rights 
while at least half of the fortune 500 firms have adopted poison 
pills designed to make unwanted takeovers prohibitively expensive 
after nearly two years of debate the sec on thursday upheld the 
one share one vote rule with a trail of caveats in an 
effort to preserve the rights of existing shareholders 
experts expect the ruling to have little impact they note that 
despite its superior ability to shield a company from hostile 
bidders supervoting stock is difficult to issue 
for one thing it had been frowned upon by the new york stock 
exchange at times banning the issuing of dual classes of stock and 
threatening to delist companies that did so 
in addition it almost always requires a shareholder vote to 
adopt a second class and management typically shies from the risk 
of rejection said robert kohl a partner at the law firm of gaston 
amp snow 
its hard to advertise to shareholders that diluting their 
voting power ultimately is a benefit institutional investors also 
would be hard to sway because they want to be able to cash in on an 
attractive bid if one happens to come alongnoted stephen flood a 
partner with the law firm of willkie farr amp gallagher 
but far deeper is the ethic that appeals to our democratic 
education about one share one vote kohl said 
some 60 companies listed on the nyse have dual classes of stock 
and the sec left those established structures intact the 
commission also will allow companies that have registered to issue 
supervoting stock to proceed with their plans 
among the public companies that have dual classes are ford motor 
co hershey foods corp wm wrigley amp co general motors corp 
and a number of media companies including dow jones amp co new 
york times co washington post co and media general inc 
kohl said the dualclass structure is most common among 
companies that have longstanding family control or foundation 
control that they want to maintain 
for example media general chairman d tennant bryan and his 
family own 71 percent of the companys class b shares which 
control six of the nine seats on the companys board the bryan 
family had little trouble in quashing california investor burt 
sugarman in a recent proxy contest for three seats on media 
generals board 
and in the case of resorts international inc donald trump 
had about 7 or 9 percent of the equity but he controled 70 percent 
of the vote flood noted that is the best defense and in a 
way the cheapest one 
entertainer merv griffin paid trump 195 million for his class b 
resorts shares each of which carried 100 times the voting power of 
a class a share 
keeping control in the hands of a founding family can have 
certain benefits though theyre not readily apparent and have to 
overcome the presumption of being democratic kohl said 
for one thing continued founding family control can ensure 
stability especially if the family has a large financial stake in 
the company you can assume it will protect that stake and that 
will protect the rest of the shareholders kohl said 
also management can engage in longer term planning which may 
involve current financial sacrifice without fear of being thrown 
out he added 
the counter argument of course is that incompetent management 
can be protected 
it is the poison pill however that has been the mainstay of 
corporate defensive tactics pills not enacted during a tender 
offer generally have been upheld in the courts kohl said while 
there has been varying success when adopted during an offer 
part of their popularity with managers may be that the pills are 
easy to enact they generally do not require shareholder approval 
the sec ruling also does not preempt antitakeover legislation 
adopted by individual states thus a company could reincorporate 
in a state whose laws affect the voting rights of shareholders 
companies still will be allowed to issue new shares with diluted 
voting power and such shares can be issued during mergers 
companies going public will be able to issue both strong and 
weakervoting shares 
stocks of foreign companies traded in the united states are 
exempt as are the less actively traded issues of small companies 
listed in the national association of securities dealers pink 
sheets 
</TEXT>
