<TEXT>
a proposal that includes coordinated trading 
halts by the nations two leading financial centers won praise 
friday from big brokers and a key member of the presidential panel 
that investigated the october stock crash but others called the 
idea a publicrelations ploy that would have little practical value 
and could actually worsen any possible future panic in the stock 
and futures markets 
the reactions came a day after the new york stock exchange and 
chicago mercantile exchange announced a broad strategy aimed at 
raising investor confidence and averting more crashes like the one 
that shook the markets on oct 19 when the dow jones industrial 
average fell a record 508 points 
their proposal for joint circuit breakers marked the first 
time since the crash that the two biggest domestic financial 
exchanges displayed open cooperation and acknowledged they are both 
part of one market 
intermarket coordination was one of the most important 
recommendations made by the presidential task force on market 
mechanisms the white house panel that reviewed the causes of the 
crash 
i think cooperation among the exchanges is whats needed in a 
world of closely interrelated markets said robert glauber a 
harvard university professor and executive director of the 
presidential study 
im very encouraged he said i think the evidence of 
cooperation between the exchanges is a tremendous step forward 
major wall street firms also applauded the moves by the big 
board and the merc as the exchanges are known in the securities 
industry several said they approved of any reform that would 
encourage reinvestment in stocks by investors who have been 
frightened out of the postcrash market 
we are especially pleased that these two market centers have 
agreed to a coordinated approach to the complex issues confronting 
all of us merrill lynch amp co said in a statement kidder 
peabody amp co president max c chapman said we endorse all 
activity that leads to an improvement of investor confidence in the 
markets 
there was no reaction from the securities and exchange 
commission one of two federal agencies that must approve the 
reforms sec commissioner joseph grundfest said he was reading the 
proposals but could not comment further 
david gary spokesman for the commodities futures trading 
commission said we applaud the cooperative effort and we think 
its a good first step we remain ready to see the specifics of the 
program when they submit it to us 
others expressed skepticism about the proposed reforms 
particularly a coordinated onehour trading halt that could be 
triggered by a 250point drop in the dow jones industrial average 
in new york or a 30point fall in the standard amp poors 500 index 
futures contract traded in chicago under the proposal subsequent 
drops in these indicators could trigger longer halts 
i may be one of the few people on wall street who will tell 
you its wonderful pr work but its useless said jack barbanel 
a futures expert at gruntal amp co in new york it really shuts 
down the doors on selling orders and causes huge backups the 
people who cant get in get doubly nervous 
if that happened critics said people who otherwise might have 
held their positions could panic and join the queues of sellers 
waiting for the markets to reopen and causing a repeated pattern of 
declines and trading halts 
youre putting in safety valves that have some significant 
practical leaks barbanel said im not to crazy about it 
glauber disputed such criticisms the fact is there are going 
to be circuit breakers whether you want them or not he said 
the choice is whether theyll be preplanned or ad hoc having 
them preplanned will induce less panic than having them ad hoc 
like computer systems failing and telephone lines backing up 
thats what occurred in october 
some market experts had a mixed reaction a few were upset that 
as part of the proposal the nyse would drop its collar 
restraint on computerized trading of large blocks of stocks and 
stockindex futures a technique known as program trading that 
has been blamed for inciting sudden price swings 
i think the spirit of what theyre doing is ok and in the 
right direction said haskel benishay professor of managerial 
economics at northwestern universitys kellogg graduate business 
school but it gives more leeway to program traders now the 
bands of noninterference are much higher 
</TEXT>
