<TEXT>
a clouded weekend weather outlook sent confidence and prices 
plummeting friday in the corn and soybean pits of the chicago board 
of trade 
on other markets livestock and meat futures were mostly lower 
energy futures were mixed precious metals were mixed and 
stockindex futures retreated 
the grain markets failure to rally on this weeks longrange 
drought forecasts for the midwest prompted many traders to grab 
profits ahead of the weekend analysts said 
the weekend forecasts were mostly bearish with some private 
forecasters increasing the amount of rain they expected to fall in 
parts of the parched farm belt over the next two days 
analysts said some traders also developed jitters ahead of 
tuesdays release of an agriculture department crop report that 
will provide tallies of this years planted acreage and revised 
crop production estimates 
but the most discouraging factor was the markets own 
performance during the week said rich feltes director of 
commodity research for refco inc a large speculative trading firm 
based in chicago 
its not the news but the markets reaction to the news 
thats most important feltes said when the market fails to 
react to bullish news it immediately injects nervousness 
disappointment and fatigue into the market 
friday marked the second consecutive session of sharply lower 
corn oat and soybean prices some corn contracts and most oat 
contracts fell their 15centsabushel limit for daily trading and 
the contract for november delivery of soybeans plunged nearly the 
45cent limit for that market wheat futures were mostly higher 
the market is perplexing said victor lespinasse a trader 
in chicago with dean witter reynolds inc its inexplicable why 
were down so hard when there isnt that much rain around and the 
temperatures are very hot maybe the market knows something we 
dont 
after the close the national weather service issued a 
6to10day outlook extending its forecast for abovenormal 
temperatures and belownormal rainfall in the midwest through july 
18 
wheat settled 4 cents lower to 9 cents higher with the contract 
for delivery in july at 386 a bushel corn was 2 cents to 15 
cents lower with july at 309 a bushel oats were 8 cents to 15 
cents lower with july at 293 a bushel soybeans were 5 cents 
lower to 40 cents lower with july at 924 a bushel 
cattle futures finished mixed on the chicago mercantile 
exchange analysts said cattle traders reacted to the drop in grain 
prices by reversing their recent trend of selling contracts for 
summer and fall delivery while bidding up the 1989 contracts 
pork futures were lower in reaction to the drop in feed grain 
prices said thomas morgan president of sterling research corp of 
arlington heights ill 
the grains are really dominating the daytoday movement in 
the cattle and hogs he said 
live cattle were 55 cent lower to 33 cent higher with august 
at 6502 cents a pound feeder cattle were 42 cent lower to 03 
cent higher with august at 7452 cents a pound hogs were 03 cent 
to 60 cent lower with july at 4537 cents a pound frozen pork 
bellies were unchanged to 160 cents lower with july at 3310 cents 
a pound 
energy futures were mixed in moderate trading on the new york 
mercantile exchange as dealers reassessed the impact of the recent 
north sea oil rig explosion on petroleum supplies and prospects for 
an emergency opec meeting diminished 
it may be a case of calmer heads prevailing today said 
peter beutel an oil analyst with elders futures inc 
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 31 cents to 37 cents 
lower with august at 1546 a barrel heating oil was 84 cent to 
90 cent lower with august at 4339 cents a gallon unleaded 
gasoline was 28 cent lower to 32 cent higher with august at 5317 
cents a gallon 
gold futures finished nearly unchanged on new yorks commodity 
exchange a sign of the markets strength in the face of falling 
crudeoil and grain prices said craig sloane an analyst with 
smith barney harris upham amp co in new york 
sloane said the labor departments report of a 03 percent drop 
in unemployment last month was potentially inflationary and 
supported preciousmetals prices 
gold was 10 cents lower to 80 cents higher with august at 441 a 
troy ounce silver was 65 cents to 85 cents higher with july at 
7 a troy ounce 
stockindex futures retreated on the chicago mercantile 
exchange where the contract for september delivery of the standard 
amp poors 500 index settled 165 points lower at 27155 
</TEXT>
